        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "b",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the place whither “the kine took the straight way” from Ekron with the Ark of the Covenant (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 6:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); where (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "c",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the people looked into the Ark and caused the severe judgment that followed (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 6:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and where (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "d",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Solomon had one of his commissariat districts (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 4:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). “Here,” at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "’Ain-Shems",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “are the vestiges of a former extensive city, consisting of many foundations, and the remains of ancient walls of hewn stone. Both the name and the position of this spot seem to indicate the site of the ancient Beth-shemesh of the Old Testament.” Robinson, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Later Bibl. Res",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". p. 153. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "β",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Timnah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Timnath",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thimnathah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), now ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Tibnah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a village about two miles west of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "’Ain-Shems",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from which Samson fetched his wife (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jdg 14:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jdg 14:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and in the vineyards of which, without anything in his hand, he killed the lion (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jdg 14:5-6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 10.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Compassed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Or, deflected (see ver. 4). This is in accordance with the view taken above. The border line which had run northwest from Jerusalem now bent backwards in a southwesterly direction, and followed the ridge towards Chesalon (see note on Chesalon). Mount Seir. Not the dwelling place of Esau, afterwards the country of the Edomites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 32:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 36:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but a range running southwestward from Kirjath-jearim, part of which is still known as Sairah, or Saris, \"auf welchem ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Saris",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " und ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Mihsir",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " liegen\" (Kuobel). Since Kirjath-jearim means the \"city of the forests,\" and Seir means \"hairy,\" we may conjecture that the name was given to the ridge on account of its wooded character. This also is implied by \"Mount Jearim.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The side of Mount Jearim.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the shoulder",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see above, ver. 8). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Which is Chesalon.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This is identified with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Kesia",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a point on the summit of the ridge stretching southwest from Kirjath-jearim. The fact that the border passed northward of Chesalon is a confirmation of the view taken above. We learn from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (cf. ver. 33 of this chapter), that the border passed by Zorah and Eshtaol in the Shephelah, through a neighbourhood described in Conder's Handbook as \"an open corn country.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Beth-shemesh.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The \"house of the sun,\" identified with the modern Ain (or fountain of) Shems. It is called Irshemesh in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It was close to the border of the Philistines, and was the scene of the transactions recorded in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The propinquity to the Philistines appears to have affected the principles of its inhabitants, and their conduct contrasts most unfavourably with that of the inhabitants of Kirjath-jearim. This was the more disgraceful, in that Beth-shemesh (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 21:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") was a priestly city, and being inhabited by those whose \"lips should keep knowledge,\" might have been expected to set a better example. It was required to furnish Solomon's household with provisions (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 4:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), it witnessed the defeat and capture of Amaziah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 14:11-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 25:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") by Joash, king of Israel. It fell into the hands of the Philistines at the time of the decay of the Jewish power under Ahaz (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 28:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The name, like Baal-Gad and Ashtaroth-Karnaim, is worthy of remark, as pointing to the character of the early Phoenician worship. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Timnah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Sometimes called Timnath in Scripture (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 14:1-6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and Timnatha in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Joshua 15:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "From this point \"the boundary (which had hitherto gone in a north-westerly direction) turned westwards to Mount Seir, and went out to the shoulder northwards (i.e., to the northern side) of Har-jearim, that is Chesalon, and went down to Beth-shemesh, and passed over to Timnah.\" Mount Seir is the ridge of rock to the south-west of Kureyet el Enab, a lofty ridge composed or rugged peaks, with a wild and desolate appearance, upon which Saris and Mishir are situated (Rob. Bibl. Res. p. 155). Chesalon is the present Kesla on the summit of a mountain, an elevated point of the lofty ridge between Wady Ghurb and Ismail, south-west of Kureyet el Enab (Rob. Bibl. Res. p. 154). Beth-shemesh (i.e., sun-house), a priests' city in the territory of Judah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 21:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 6:44",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is the same as Ir-shemesh (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), a place on the border of Dan, where the ark was deposited by the Philistines (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 6:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".), and where Amaziah was slain by Joash (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 14:11-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 25:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It was conquered by the Philistines in the time of Ahaz (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 28:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). According to the Onom. it was ten Roman miles, i.e., four hours, from Eleutheropolis towards Nicopolis. It is the present Ain Shems, upon a plateau in a splendid situation, two hours and a half to the south-west of Kesla (Rob. Pal. iii. p. 17; Bibl. Res. p. 153). Timnah, or Timnatah, belonged to Dan (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:43",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and it was thence that Samson fetched his wife (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 14:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".). It is the present Tibneh, three-quarters of an hour to the west of Ain Shems (Rob. Pal. i. p. 344).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]